<TEXT>
democratic presidential frontrunner michael dukakis wrapped up 
a california campaign swing sunday as his persistent rival jesse 
jackson pointedly told black students never surrender 
republican george bush meanwhile hung out the gone fishing 
sign 
jackson and dukakis were bracing for a primary battle on tuesday 
in oregon with 45 democratic delegates up for grabs a poll last 
month suggested dukakis was leading but jackson has campaigned 
hard in oregon drawing huge enthusiastic crowds 
jackson planned a final swing through the state on monday but 
dukakis was scheduled to devote the eve of the primary to taking 
care of gubernatorial business in massachusetts 
bush spent several hours sunday fishing from a raft on the rogue 
river in oregon with the secret service and a floating press corps 
for company he didnt catch any fish though 
the vice president was flying to seattle for an evening rally 
washington was the only state the vice president lost on super 
tuesday 
bushs sole remaining rival pat robertson who stayed in the 
race long after he fell from contention was poised to formally 
halt his bid on monday 
the vice president attained a mathematical lock on the 
nomination last month in the pennsylvania primary and picked up 
the endorsement of his boss president reagan last week robertson 
endorsed him too 
both dukakis and jackson were making brief stops sunday in new 
jersey which along with california holds a highstakes contest 
on june 7 the last day of the primary season 
i smell victory in the air an upbeat dukakis told a crowd 
at the new jersey democratic convention in south orange 
appearing before the same group jackson without naming 
dukakis criticized his rivals record as massachusetts governor 
and declared ive earned every vote ive gained 
the two met briefly before their new jersey appearances and 
dukakis described their exchange as warm pleasant respectful 
california with its primary prize of 314 democratic and 175 
republican delegates has been a frequent stumping ground for the 
presidential trio all three had appearances in the state last week 
dukakis who left california sunday after two days of 
campaigning got a lessthanfriendly reception on saturday from 
gay activists in los angeles the governor was grilled about his 
reluctance to allow homosexual couples to act as foster parents 
he planned to return to california later in the week as did 
jackson 
aides to dukakis are hoping the last big contests in california 
and new jersey will put dukakis over the top in terms of delegates 
according to the latest ap delegate count dukakis has 1610 to 
jacksons 956 of 2081 needed to nominate 
dukakis refuses to discount jacksons continuing candidacy but 
his talk has focused more and more on an expected confrontation 
with bush in november 
i think the fact that in these early matchups between me and 
the vice president the fact that i am leading at least gives you 
some sense that this is doable dukakis said over the 
weekend referring to polls suggesting that he could beat bush in 
the fall 
jackson was in hampton va on sunday giving a graduation 
address at predominantly black hampton university his 61yearold 
motherinlaw gertrude brown was receiving her degree in social 
work at the ceremony 
jackson who has pushed ahead with his campaign despite a string 
of losses to dukakis cited mrs brown as someone who has overcome 
obstacles and succeeded 
she is of strong character and she never surrendered said 
jackson who told of his motherinlaws struggle to raise five 
children while working full time three of those children he said 
went on to receive advanced degrees 
when her last child left home mrs brown returned to get her 
high school diploma at age 49 over the next 12 years she 
completed her college education 
against all odds she is graduating today that is what 
this graduation is all about jackson said never surrender 
he told the students that if elected he would double federal 
spending on education 
</TEXT>
