<TEXT>
us experts on the soviet union expect little 
from the moscow summit and are looking beyond it to an early summer 
communist party conference which by all accounts will be a 
watershed in soviet politics 
mikhail s gorbachev appears likely to survive for at least a 
couple more years as the partys general secretary but he has 
failed to gain full control of the policymaking central committee 
the 300plus member body that so far has stymied his farreaching 
reform efforts according to the experts 
they view the summit primarily as part of gorbachevs effort to 
cement his control 
gorbachevs reforms so far have not improved soviet living 
standards according to western dispatches from moscow and a recent 
analysis by the central intelligence agency 
his biggest success has been in the foreign policy arena 
improving the image of the soviet union around the world by 
improving relations with the united states by making arms control 
proposals and by agreeing to withdraw the red army from afghanistan 
he can brighten his own image further at home and abroad by 
playing host in the kremlin to a smiling ronald reagan who built a 
career on anticommunism and who began his presidency by branding 
the soviet union the evil empire 
probably the most important thing gorbachev needs is the 
symbolism of having ronald reagan in moscow said marshall 
shulman a columbia university lecturer and a top carter 
administration expert on soviet affairs 
american and soviet officials have lowered public expectations 
for the summit as the senate delayed ratification of an arms 
control treaty signed last december and us and soviet negotiators 
remain far apart on a proposed pact to sharply cut strategic 
arsenals 
but said a senior government analyst who spoke on condition of 
anonymity both parties want to see the summit come off smoothly 
they dont want any embarrassments they have made progress in the 
relationship 
shulman agreed that a successful symbolic summit would be 
useful for gorbachev but it would not solve his problems his 
basic problems are rooted in the domestic economy 
a summit marred by disagreements on the other hand could 
weaken gorbachevs case at home said the senior us government 
analyst 
the ferment in the soviet leadership is as great as at any 
time since the 1920s said the government expert but this 
will not be played out at the summit we wont see much disarray 
there 
gorbachev and his chief rival on the ruling politburo yegor 
ligachev are expected to maintain their harmonious front at least 
through the summit said the analyst 
that is unless gorbachev manages to ease ligachev from the 
powerful party secretariat into the largely ceremonial post of 
president now held by andrei gromyko another politburo member 
thought to be wary of sweeping reforms 
under this scenario which could be played out at meetings of 
the central committee and the supreme soviet expected the week 
before the may 29june 2 summit ligachev would probably remain in 
the politburo but gromyko would not 
however the central committee has been a thorn in gorbachevs 
side and may balk at leadership changes until he can gain greater 
control over it 
at the most recent party congress in early 1987 gorbachev 
replaced about 40 percent of the central committee but needs to 
fill another 15 to 20 percent of the seats with his people for a 
comfortable majority said shulman 
the party conference is his chance to do that 
some of the 5000 or so conference delegates have been selected 
by local and regional communist party bodies and gorbachev has 
started trying to unselect those he believes will oppose him 
said shulman 
since gorbachev rose to power in march 1985 the central 
committee has balked at some his most radical ideas such as 
limiting the tenure of party officials having secret ballots and 
allowing more than one candidate for elections 
gorbachev wants to push those through and persuade the committee 
to accept his view on what the soviets call the question of 
questions what the role of the party will be said shulman just 
back from moscow 
gorbachev agreed the senior government analyst would like 
the party out of the details he wants the party to have 
macrovision not to micromanage 
gorbachevs vision as perceived by shulman and the government 
analyst is for the communist party whose members now make up 10 
percent of the population to set broad policy and exercise 
general control over the country 
the central committee many of whose members are the 
middlelevel managers whose role gorbachev seeks to reduce so far 
have balked at surrendering the partys minutebyminute control 
over all soviet institutions 
</TEXT>
