prospects for economic growth are good 
this year but interest rates if they continue to rise threaten to 
topple the united states into a recession by the end of 1989 the 
countrys business leaders say 
most members of the business council composed of 61 chief 
executives of some of the nations largest companies say business 
so far in 1988 is better than they expected at the end of 1987 
when many were worried about the effects of the october stock 
market crash 
now the executives with the exception of those heading 
financial service firms such as brokerage and insurance companies 
report signs of moderate or better growth 
the car business is going great actually stronger than any of 
us anticipated said roger b smith chairman of general motors 
corp 
other executives attending the councils twiceayear meeting 
last weekend at the homestead a posh resort in the mountains of 
western virginia echoed smiths sentiments reporting other signs 
of strong demand 
were seeing a surprising increase in demand for motor 
gasoline in the united states at least 2 percentage points above 
what we expected said george m keller chairman of chevron corp 
but amid the satisfaction over the countrys more than 
5yearold business expansion the longest since the 1960s was 
concern that possible renewed inflation could trigger rising 
interest rates 
charles w parry retired chairman of the aluminum company of 
america said prices of metals chemicals and other basic 
commodities are up significantly 
such a rise often has been a precursor of an increase in 
inflation rates and that has me a little bit worried parry 
said 
a forecast representing a consensus of economists employed by 
business council member companies predicts modest growth as 
measured by the gross national product of 24 percent this year 
that compares with 38 percent in 1987 
a inflationary signs remain muted the economists said 
predicting a rise in consumer prices of 39 percent this year and 
46 percent in 1989 compared with 44 percent last year 
however the economists sounded a warning that overly robust 
growth could produce an unavoidable rise in interest rates and a 
recession before the end of 1989 
underscoring the warning major banks raised their prime lending 
rate from 85 percent to 9 percent only two days before the council 
began its meeting 
interest rates already seem to be outstripping the councils 
forecasts which were prepared about a week in advance of the 
conference 
the average yield on 30year bonds issued by the treasury last 
week was 917 percent the executives were looking for an average 
rate on 30year bonds of 89 percent this year and 93 percent next 
year 
