<TEXT>
a parasitic mite attacking bee colonies around the 
country threatens to leave americas cranberry growers without 
enough bees for pollination this year and hurt production of other 
crops and honey officials say 
massachusetts the nations leader in cranberry production is 
hiring more bee inspectors to keep out the pinheadsize mite known 
as varroa jacobsoni which can quickly destroy bee colonies and has 
been found in 13 states 
there wont be enough bees for a good thorough job of 
pollination said irving demoranville director of the university 
of massachusetts cranberry experiment station in wareham 
the nations more than 900 cranberry growers last year produced 
350 million pounds valued at 188 million according to david 
farrimond general manager of the warehambased cranberry marketing 
committee 
growers rely on migratory beekeepers now heading north for work 
pollinating fruit and vegetable crops this spring and summer 
last month the federal government imposed a quarantine on 
interstate bee transportation in the 13 states about six months 
after the varroa mite was detected in wisconsin but the quarantine 
was lifted after proving too costly and unmanageable and 
inspection was turned over to states 
we clearly did not have a workable quarantine to assure that 
we were going to be able to control the spread we found it likely 
that a lot of them were going to move their bees regardless said 
nancy robinson spokeswoman for the us department of 
agricultures animal and plant health inspection sevice 
beekeepers eager to assuage growers are taking out ads in 
cranberries magazine a national trade publication saying their 
bees are clean 
cranberry growers say beekeepers with contaminated bees who 
cross state lines could spead the infestation massachusetts 
farmers say the mite has reached the state although that has not 
been confirmed 
growers say the spread of the mite could have a longterm impact 
on fruit vegetable and honey production 
there is a lot of concern said douglas beaton president of 
the cape cod cranberry growers association if it goes unchecked 
then our crops will most surely be threatened in two or three 
years 
massachusetts last year produced 160 million pounds of 
cranberries worth 83 milllion on 11600 acres according to state 
food and agriculture department figures ninetyeight percent of 
the crop depends on wild domestic honeybees for pollination 
the national cranberry crop would suffer a 30 percent to 50 
percent drop without bees to pollinate them said jon gottschalk a 
phillips wis cranberry grower and board member of ocean spray 
cranberries inc the industry cooperative 
as apple buds begin to blossom in massachusetts this month 
migratory beekeepers from out of state have started arriving and 
their bees and equipment are being checked for the mite 
the state has hired two inspectors to monitor migratory 
beekeepers said peter c kuzmiski chief of the state plant and 
pest control bureau he said five or six inspectors would be on 
duty by midjune when cranberries begin to blossom 
beekeepers are not optimistic about preventing the mites spread 
theres no way possible that they will keep them out of the 
state said joseph mello past president of the massachusetts 
federation of beekeepers they will make it in and eventually we 
will have the problem throughout the entire state its a problem 
that will be here to stay 
the federal environmental protection agency in january approved 
use of the chemical fluvalinate to fumigate bees and hives for the 
mites a plastic strip containing fluvalinate kills the mite but 
not enough is believed to be available to treat all the bees now 
contaminated 
the varroa mite is an external parasite of adult bees and their 
developing larvae it decreases the number of larvae deforms bees 
and weakens a colonys ability to pollinate plants and produce 
honey 
the 13 states where the bee mite has been found are florida 
illinois maine michigan mississippi nebraska new york ohio 
pennsylvania south carolina south dakota washington and 
wisconsin 
in addition to honey production a bee shortage would reduce 
pollination of apples blueberries cucumbers squash and other 
fuits and vegetables 
