<TEXT>
high above downtown two wild peregrine falcon 
chicks pecked out of their shells in a nest on a skyscraper ledge 
to baltimoreans the hatching of another clutch of the 
endangered species is almost old hat a pair of peregrines have 
been raising families on the 33rdfloor ledge of the united states 
fidelity amp guaranty corp building since 1984 and at least one 
peregrine has lived on the building since 1979 
but the migration of falcons to cities is a surprising 
development in a successful experiment begun by cornell university 
in 1970 to reintroduce the predatory bird to southern canada and 
the continental united states after ddt and other pesticides 
decimated the species 
baltimore was the first city the falcons chose the first of the 
birds which were raised in captivity drifted down from a new 
jersey marsh the latest chicks were hatched two weeks ago by 
falcons named blythe and beauregard 
