<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand an 
arbitrators reinstatement of an airline pilot fired for allegedly 
flying drunk 
the justices without comment refused to use the case of former 
northwest airlines pilot larry w morrison to study the power of 
federal courts to overturn labor arbitrators awards deemed 
contrary to public policy 
in deciding a case from louisiana last year the court adhered 
to previous rulings that limit severely such federal court power 
the court unanimously ruled that an arbitrators award may be 
overturned on public policy grounds only when the award creates an 
explicit conflict with laws or legal precedent 
last month the justices backed out of reaching a public 
policy grounds decision in the case of a postal service letter 
carrier reinstated after he was fired for failing to deliver more 
than 3500 pieces of mail 
in the pilots case morrison was fired for violating his 
employers policy against drinking alcoholic beverages within 24 
hours of flying 
a northwest pilot for 16 years morrison was given a blood test 
more than two hours after serving as a copilot on a jetliner 
flight carrying 79 people from las vegas to san francisco on aug 
1 1982 his blood alcohol level was enough to create a presumption 
of intoxication under california law 
morrison through the air line pilots association challenged 
his ensuing dismissal the challenge said he was fired without 
just cause because his misconduct was the unavoidable 
consequence of his alcoholism 
northwest allows reformed alcoholics to be pilots but the 
airline said morrison failed to seek help until his problem had 
endangered lives and so he had to be fired 
morrison has since completed a treatment program successfully 
the federal aviation administration has ruled him eligible to 
resume piloting commercial aircraft 
an airline arbitration board in 1984 ordered northwest to 
reinstate morrison but us district judge joyce hens green here 
reversed that ruling in 1985 
she said morrisons reinstatement would be contrary to public 
policy 
the us circuit court of appeals here reversed the trial 
judges ruling last year 
the appeals court interpreted a key 1983 ruling by the supreme 
court to mean that an arbitrators award contravenes public policy 
only if the award itself violates a law or compels unlawful conduct 
in seeking supreme court review northwest lawyers said the 
appeals courts ruling in morrisons case conflicts with other 
federal appeals court interpretations of the justices 1983 
decision 
northwests appeal argued that the ruling in morrisons case is 
based on a crimped view of the public policy exception created 
in the 1983 decision 
the case is northwest airlines vs air line pilots association 
861548 
