<TEXT>
states may tax the costs of producing 
merchandise catalogs mailed directly to instate residents even 
when the catalogs are published in other states the supreme court 
ruled today 
the court unanimously rejected a department store chains 
attempt to avoid paying taxes for catalogs received by its 
louisiana customers 
writing for the court chief justice william h rehnquist said 
louisianas imposition of a use tax on catalogs produced for 
the new orleansbased dh holmes co does not interfere unduly 
with interstate commerce 
the louisiana tax structure does not discriminate against 
interstate commerce rehnquist wrote the use tax is designed 
to compensate the state for revenue lost when residents purchase 
outofstate goods for use within the state it is equal to the 
sales tax applicable to the same tangible personal property 
purchased instate 
the chief justice also noted that holmes with 13 department 
stores in louisiana initiated the catalog deliveries to improve 
its sales and namerecognition among louisiana residents 
he said the department store chains significant presence in 
louisiana provided what lawyers call the required nexus 
contact with the state to justify the tax 
there is nexus aplenty here rehnquist said 
the court rejected arguments that because holmes never actually 
possessed the catalogs it never really owned them and therefore 
should not be subject to the tax 
dh holmes co also operates stores in mississippi alabama and 
florida but 82 percent of its catalogs are mailed to about 400000 
louisiana customers 
the state tax imposed on holmes is based on 82 percent of the 
catalogs value the company paid more than 2 million to produce 
the catalogs for three years 
todays decision upheld state court rulings that the tax is 
valid 
the case is dh holmes co vs mcnamara 87267 
