<TEXT>
a book preservation technique developed by the 
library of congress shows promise but alternatives should be 
considered also according to a study by the federal office of 
technology assessment 
acids in the types of paper used to print books over the last 
century or so threaten to destroy the volumes some in as little as 
50 years according to the study made public last week 
chemists working for the library developed a system using 
diethylzinc vapors to remove this acid from books the study said 
this has worked successfully 
however diethylzinc is a dangerous chemical which bursts into 
flame on contact with air the pilot plant where it was made was 
destroyed by fire and it would have to be used in a specially 
enclosed environment filled with nitrogen gas ota said in its 
study prepared for congress 
on the plus side dez vapors permeate closed books so it can be 
used to process large numbers of books stacked together 
but the study adds since the development of the dez process 
the library has done very little to look into alternatives 
although two other book deacidification systems also are under 
development those alternatives may merit consideration the report 
said 
ota which is an analytical agency serving congress said the 
acid in modern book paper causes brittleness and eventual crumbling 
of the paper already the agency says 25 percent of the librarys 
14 million books are too brittle for regular use 
books can be copied onto magnetic tape microfilm or optical 
discs but those are more costly and more difficult to use than 
paper volumes the study said 
while chemical treatments can stop books from becoming more 
brittle they do not repair damage that already has occurred and 
the library is working on a process for strengthening already 
damaged paper 
the eventual solution the report added would be use of 
acidfree paper in book printing that is being done for between 15 
percent and 25 percent of books published currently 
</TEXT>
