<TEXT>
if peace ever returns to the mountains 
and deserts of afghanistan the warravaged country will require 
one of the most massive reconstruction efforts since world war ii 
the first stage will be the relocation of about 3 million afghan 
refugees from pakistan and 2 million from iran western observers 
believe that 4 million more afghans are refugees inside their own 
country 
anthony land head of the peshawar pakistan office of the un 
high commissioner for refugees said the return will be the largest 
human migration in the organizations history 
inside afghanistan 10 years of civil war between the communist 
government and moslem insurgents the last 8 years with soviet 
military involvement have left much of the country in ruins 
pakistanis western diplomats guerrillas and refugees seem to 
agree that even if the fighting stops in afghanistan the country 
will never be the same 
gulbaddin hekmatyar chairman of the sevenparty guerrilla 
alliance based in pakistan estimated that 60 percent of the houses 
in afghanistan have been destroyed along with an equal percentage 
of arable land 
the whole country is in ruins said the guerrilla leader 
canals and irrigation systems are badly damaged or destroyed 
hekmatyar said the afghans ability to restore the irrigation 
systems will be crucial to avoid mass starvation once the refugees 
return 
un agencies and several countries have started making plans 
for afghanistans reconstruction but they say it is too early 
gauge the projects exact size or expense 
one of the first and most dangerous tasks will be clearing mines 
planted or scattered across the countryside by sovietafghan 
aircraft 
us diplomats estimate there may be 3 million of them the 
guerrillas say the number is closer to 55 million 
then comes what officials predict will be a massive infusion of 
emergency food and shelter medical supplies seeds and farm 
implements 
some officials believe that fields left fallow under years of 
blazing sun will be too hard to be worked by the afghans 
traditional wooden plows 
few officials care to venture what all this will cost but the 
un high commissioner for refugees jeanpierre hocke recently 
mentioned a figure of 300 million western diplomats in islamabad 
have guessed up to 15 billion dollars 
when the refugees return is anybodys guess but several 
interviewed in the camps of pakistans northwest frontier province 
said they wont venture back until all soviets are gone and the 
marxist kabul government has fallen 
i will go first and see what is left of my home and my farm 
said isayal ghairad 34 who lives with his wife two daughters and 
son in the sunbaked munda no 6 camp a halfhours drive from 
peshawar 
he said he will not send for his family until he is certain he 
can feed and house them 
un and pakistani officials agree they wont see the refugee 
exodus begin until after next springs thaw 
a squabble has already broken out over which government the 
reconstruction aid should be channeled through the existing kabul 
regime islamabad or the guerrillas who are creating a government 
of their own 
