<TEXT>
the federal communications commission has 
exclusive authority to regulate the technical quality of cable 
television signals the supreme court ruled unanimously today 
the court rejected arguments that state and local officials 
should be allowed to impose more stringent requirements for cable 
tv 
the commission acted within the statutory authority conferred 
by congress when it preempted state and local technical standards 
governing the quality of cable television signals said justice 
byron r white for the court 
the fcc has divided cable services into four categories the 
first consists of cable channels that deliver signals of television 
stations that are normally broadcast through the air 
the other classes include cable channels such as cable news 
network and espn pay channels such as home box office and 
channels with twoway capability that allow subscribers to return 
information to the channel control point 
the us circuit court of appeals ruled last year that the fcc 
has exclusive control over the signal quality of the first class of 
cable channels the appeals court also ordered the fcc to develop 
standards for assuring the quality of the signals in the latter 
three categories 
the first part of the appeals court ruling was appealed to the 
supreme court by the national league of cities new york city 
officials and other communities 
they said state county and city governments should be allowed 
to impose signal quality standards for cable channels that carry 
television broadcast stations 
the supreme court ruled today that a 1984 federal law does not 
bar the fcc from preempting such authority from state and local 
governments 
the justices said the statute endorses a dual system of cable tv 
regulation giving local officials power to award franchises but 
leaving control over technical quality of cable signals with the 
fcc 
cable systems operate in more than 18500 communities 
the fcc said giving local control over technical matters could 
impede the growth of cable tv by imposing overly burdensome 
requirements and would subject cable operators to a patchwork of 
different rules 
the challenge to the fccs power by new york city and the 
national league of cities was supported by officials from miami 
wheaton ill dallas scottsdale ariz st louis montgomery 
county md and sacramento calif 
the case is new york city vs fcc 87339 
</TEXT>
