seventyfive hunters won a lottery monday 
to participate in new hampshires first moose hunt since 1901 
i wont be hunting moose but ill be out there in the 
woods said a disappointed bernard durant who was among a dozen 
hunters who watched as a computer selected the winners from 5900 
applicants 
the random selection at fish and game department headquarters 
gives 65 residents and 10 outofstate hunters a chance to shoot 
one of the animals 
fish and game officials proposed the threeday hunt to manage 
the herd conservatively estimated at 1600 the population has 
rebounded after being decimated in the late 1800s 
opponents contend the hunt is being allowed simply to satisfy 
hunters moose are so docile that shooting one is like shooting a 
parked car they claim 
fish and game officials say the animals appear tame on the 
roadside but are cagey in the woods howard nowell chief of game 
management research denies the state was pressured by hunters 
new hampshires house this year killed legislation aimed at 
stopping the hunt after a colorful debate that included a moose 
call by one lawmaker meant to rally support for the hunt 
opponents were not nearly as vocal as those in neighboring maine 
when that state introduced a moose hunt in 1980 maine then studied 
the issue for a year before voters overwhelmingly approved an 
annual hunt beginning in 1982 in maine 1000 hunters are chosen 
by lottery and opposition has virtually ceased 
six other states hold annual moose hunts alaska montana 
idaho north dakota utah and wyoming minnesota has one every 
other year oregon colorado and washington also have allowed moose 
hunting 
