<TEXT>
the federal government is planning regulations 
requiring operators of city transit buses and subways to be subject 
to a broad range of drug tests including random tests a senior 
department official said monday 
alfred dellibovi head of the urban mass transportation 
administration said local transit officials who fail to develop a 
testing program for drugs would face the loss of federal transit 
subsidies 
the federal regulations that are being prepared call on transit 
officials to test for illegal use of drugs during preemployment 
after an accident for reasonable cause and under a random 
selection process according to dellibovi 
operators of buses and subway trains as well as others in 
sensitive jobs such as train dispatchers would be subject to 
the testing he said 
the federal agency which dellibovi heads provides federal 
financial assistance to transit systems although a testing program 
would have to be imposed and administered by the local transit 
authorities 
dellibovi outlined his agencys plans in a speech before the 
american public transit associations annual education conference 
he noted a recent finding by investigators in the april 6 crash 
of a commuter train in new york city in which traces of illegal 
drugs were found in five employees involved in the accident 
including the trains engineer and the dispatcher 
similar horror stories may have occurred in your own area 
dellibovi told the transit officials in st louis according to a 
copy of his speech released through his office in washington 
dellibovi criticized the transit industry for not tackling the 
drug testing issue instead he said the industry has been 
debating the merits of permitting passengers to smoke in the back 
of the trains 
the recent new york accident is only the current victim of an 
industrywide failure to tackle the tough issue of random drug 
testing he said all too often this reluctance to take on 
such a distasteful issue produces an ineffective antidrug 
program instead of a steadfast policy 
dellibovi gave no timetable on when the federal drug testing 
requirements would be announced formally or go into effect but he 
said they will require that local transit authorities 
aggressively enforce them or face the loss of federal financial 
assistance 
