the department of energy may have engaged in a 
cover up when it failed to include data on radioactive iodine 
contamination in an environmental report on the hanford nuclear 
reservation sen mark hatfield said monday 
hatfield rore said the general accounting office found the 
departments handling of information on iodine 129 contamination in 
the groundwater beneath the reservation in south central washington 
state was dominated by a pattern of activity that generally 
discouraged disseminating the information within or outside the 
agency 
at a news conference hatfield said the gao report wont be 
released until the energy department has had a chance to comment 
but hatfield said he was told in a briefing by officials of the 
congressional watchdog agency that the pattern of activity was so 
pervasive at doe that the information may never have been 
publicly released had not people outside the agency pursued the 
issue 
while the words cover up were not specifically used in the 
report i dont know of a better phrase to describe the 
actitvity hatfield said 
will callicott a doe spokesman said our own inspector 
generals office has looked at this before and could find nothing 
to substantiate any allegation of a cover up 
the environmental assessment of the hanford reservation was 
released in 1986 when hanford was under consideration as one of 
three sites for the nations first highlevel nuclear waste dump 
hatfield said there were indications that doe was well aware of 
the iodine contamination when it issued the environmental 
assessment though it made no mention of the problem 
we do not know specifically who orchestrated this situation 
but gao did inform us that there is no evidence to suggest that 
this activity was the result of directives from the upper echelons 
of doe hatfield said i suspect there were individuals who 
didnt want the truth known 
hatfield said someone at doe decided the information on the 
iodine contamination was not important enough to include in the 
environmental report he also suggested the omission may have been 
aimed at casting hanford in a favorable light to validate the 
departments selection of the reservation as a possible site for 
the nuclear waste repository 
