<TEXT>
 
editors note every kid with a cane pole and a can of worms 
knows the joy of fishing one of four americans fish for fun among 
them the selfanointed elite are the 64 million fly fishermen to 
them hooking a trout can be like a religious experience and their 
numbers are growing along with their passion this is the first of 
three articles 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
as johnny france remembers it he was a boy 
roaming wild in the bear trap canyon when he first saw her 
she was standing up on her hind legs staring straight down 
into the river as it swirled around her every once in a while her 
big paw would shoot out splashing her but she kept coming up 
emptyhanded either missing completely or the slippery trout 
would wiggle out of her grasp after a very long time completely 
frustrated and still hungry that old sow grizzly let out an angry 
growl shook herself off and walked away in disgust 
france likes to tell that tall tale to the fly fishermen he 
guides down the madison river of montana it is his homegrown 
homily about the humblings of nature on man and beast his tactful 
way of saying fly fishing is the great leveler it is merciless 
toward ceos yuppies onehorse cowpokes and grizzly bears alike 
france especially likes to spin his yarn on days when the fish 
arent biting 
2994 trout per mile exclaims the state of montana in 
halfpage advertisements in fishing magazines adding its own 
codicil for doubting thomases honestaverage from five 
selected montana rivers 
the ad implies that fishing is so easy in montana even a child 
can do it but a fly fisherman puts away childish things like 
night crawlers and grasshoppers 
boys should learn about trout after they have learned about 
girls wrote geoffrey norman in a fishermans seasons 
trout and trout rivers are sensuous and unpredictable they 
frustrate more than they reward and they have a way of making you 
feel inadequate 
so to be a fly fisherman is to surrender to the complexities of 
30000 fly patterns the more than 130 different fly rods sold by 
the orvis company alone and all the nuance and subtlety of the 
sport it is sometimes to be skunked to go home with an empty 
creel and dreams of the one that got away 
whenever we touched the banks of the yellowstone river great 
numbers of trout were seen of enormous size swimming in water 
which was so clear that every motion of the fish could be 
distinctly seenselecting my lightest fly rod my reel and line 
were soon attachedthe trout were there i knew and i expected 
to hook one the instant the flies struck but i was doomed to 
disappointment there was no responsei tried every color in my 
book but to no purposei spent an hour without a single rise 
and at length gave it up 
thus wrote gen william strong in 1875 during a military 
expedition through the yellowstone country of montana and wyoming 
american indians fished for food long before plymouth rock but 
fly fishing was imported by british and european immigrants 
theres evidence it was practiced for sport on eastern rivers as 
far back as the revolutionary war 
in much of the old country most good fishing streams are 
privately owned with no public access democracy gave all citizens 
the right to fish the united states public waters that equality 
explains why one in four are now fishermen anybody with a pole a 
line and a hook and who buys a license can fish on 729 million 
acres of federal state and municipal public lands 
but on some days when the wind isnt just right or the light 
is wrong or the great fish god simply decrees no not in this 
space and time there will be no taut lines stopped hearts or 
sparkling rainbows flashing through the air 
the true mystery of fly fishing is why any trout salmon 
steelhead a seagoing rainbow trout bass or bonefish is ever 
caught by a man or woman dressed up in rubber britches 
it kinda makes you wonder why a fish would pick you mused 
france a 47yearold cowboy and former sheriff whos fished his 
whole life 
why with all the billions of bugs flying around and under the 
water would a big brown trout decide to eat mine 
because france knows how to read water how to match live 
mosquitoes with the dead feathers and hair he ties on his hook how 
to predict the time and distance in a fishs life 
to know what he knows is a quest which sets millions of men and 
more and more women off in search of perfect equipment perfect 
rivers the anglers equivalent of biblical tomes and companions 
with whom to share the passion and wonder which envelops an angler 
the instant he hooks his first fish on an artificial fly 
it was an employment for his idle time which was then not 
idly spent wrote fly fishings first guru izaac walton in 
the compleat angler 
a rest to his mind a cheerer of his spirits a diverter of 
sadness a calmer of unquiet thoughts a moderator of passions a 
procurrer of contentednessand that it begat habits of peace and 
patience in those that professed and practiced it 
three centuries later norman maclean published a slim volume 
containing a novella and two short stories titled a river runs 
through it which has become another classic of the genre 
in our family there was no clear line between religion and 
fly fishing maclean wrote we lived at the junction of great 
trout rivers in western montana and our father was a presbyterian 
minister and a fly fisherman who tied his own flies and taught 
others he told us about christs disciples being fishermen and we 
were left to assume as my brother and i did that all firstclass 
fishermen on the sea of galilee were fly fishermen and that john 
the favorite was a dryfly fisherman 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0244 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
dry flies being in the lexicon of the sport the equivalent of 
the shootout at the ok corral because they are little fake bugs 
which float on top of the water and dare a fish to show itself when 
it comes after them 
wet flies which are made of more absorbent materials sink 
below the surface and therefore arent considered as much fun by 
purists 
and purists there are by the hundreds of thousands unlike 
plunk and dunkers who use live bait or shiny lures to spincast for 
catfish bluegills yellow perch and black crappie fly fishermen 
are elitists 
it isnt money that sets them apart from other fishermen 
although kings and presidents have commonly been fly fishermen 
never mind that today a serious or just plain rich angler can 
spend thousands on equipment and costume 
no say fly fishermen theirs is an intellectual exercise as 
much as a physical workout it is a sport where no one keeps score 
an avocation demanding as much concentration as a hostile takeover 
or a friendly merger 
calling fishing a hobby is like calling brain surgery a job 
said paul schullery author of the new book american fly fishing 
a history 
the curious may collect hundreds of volumes on the subject 
dating from a treatise on fishing with a hook attributed to 
dame juliana berneres in 1496 to tom rosenbauers reading trout 
streams which is still in print 
some of americas noted writers ernest hemingway zane grey 
and artists winslow homer n c wyeth labored to transmit to the 
unenlightened the joy and frustrations of fly fishing 
research can sometimes carry zealots to the outside of the 
envelope professional angler a j mcclane has wet a line in 141 
countries and lived with eskimos and pygmies to learn techniques 
author and publisher nick lyons wearing goggles once submerged 
himself in a full bathtub to get a troutseye view he said he 
didnt learn much 
the more the mystery deepens the more the magic beckons 
some fly fishermen especially after a great day on a fine 
river guess that the attraction is linked to mans primeval 
origins they wax poetic about the thrill of the hunt the 
oneonone battle with a wild creature sometimes they compare the 
experience to love 
ive guided on the new fork river of wyoming for 25 years 
but ive never landed a trophy on her lamented jack dennis jr 
of jackson wy theres a certain mystery to that river like 
wondering whatever happened to the girl you loved in high school 
but didnt marry 
increasingly fly fishermen say the thrill of catching a trout 
or a steelhead is nearly matched by releasing it to hook again some 
other day on the sections of rivers designated gold medal and blue 
ribbon by various agencies barbless hooks and catchandrelease 
regulations are the norm rather than the exception 
because coldwater game fish need clear clean water to survive 
they can often be seen gliding just below the surface every year 
nearly 180000 visitors to yellowstone national park peer over the 
edge of fishing bridge where angling is outlawed to watch the 
fish go by just watch 
the roman poet martial a d 40104 may have been the first to 
use a feathered hook to land a saltwater fish a hundred years 
later macedonian fishermen reportedly were catching trout on fake 
flies 
through the ages fishermen landed countless catches using all 
kinds of artificial creations fly tying itself became an art 
in 1658 richard franck who served in oliver cromwells army 
noted that the salmon delights in the most gaudy and orient 
colors you can choose 
mary ellen orvis marbury whose father charles orvis founded 
the nations oldest mailorder company in 1856 was the first 
person to organize and categorize fly patterns used in the united 
states she exhibited her own handtied flies at the columbian 
world exposition in chicago in 1893 
todays artificial flies imitate anything from a tiny egg to 
snails hundreds are on display at the american museum of fly 
fishing in manchester vt which houses the history of the sport 
in the new world 
men women and children who wade into a trout stream do it for 
their own reasons but all are bound by unifying skeins there is 
peace in such places the outer peace of scenery the inner peace 
of reflection 
for a fly fisherman standing kneedeep in a swiftly flowing 
stream of melted snow or a crystalline lake there is harmony with 
earth and sky a condition increasingly rare in this hightech 
highdensity world 
never mind if its raining never mind if the wind blows glory 
be if its bracing blue skies if the trees on the bank are tender 
green or autumnal gold if the breeze is a caress 
never mind if the trout arent biting or the salmon arent 
running they did yesterday they will tomorrow if theres one 
commandment all fly fishermen believe in it is the optimism of 
tomorrow 
for that is the day they will finally land all the ones that got 
away 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0245 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
more and more often the peace and 
tranquility of worldclass trout streams near here are being 
invaded by the distant shriek and explosion of military training 
its a collision of two worlds both economically vital to the 
2000 residents of this northern lower peninsula town surrounded by 
woods and winding rivers 
northeast of town is camp grayling the nations secondlargest 
national guard training post there men and women from across the 
country train for battle 
also to the northeast are branches of the au sable river 
classified by outdoors magazines as being among the top fly fishing 
streams in the nation there men and women seek the serenity of a 
shallow river twisting through wooded hills a favorite habitat of 
the trout 
for nearly 75 years the two sides have coexisted in relative 
harmony but recently as the post expands its mission to include 
some wintertime training and resort development expands its 
holdings they have butted into each other 
within five miles of some small communities made up partly of 
summertime cabins along the au sable and manistee rivers are 
ranges the guard periodically bombards with artillery and 
airtoground shells 
the guard mostly uses marker bombs with a small explosive 
charge and plenty of dye to show where a bomb hit sometimes the 
real thing bombs containing up to 500 pounds of explosives are 
used 
the guard activity the night firing and everything else that 
goes on totally destroys the ambiance of the fly fishermen on the 
river says dan alstott president of the ausable manistee action 
council a coalition of conservationists and other groups 
the branches of the au sable which means to the sands in 
french wind their way east to lake huron 
rusty gates president of the anglers of the au sable runs the 
16room gates fishing lodge on the river where the trout season 
runs from late april through october fish may be caught and 
released anytime during the year however 
weve had flames 150 feet high right across the river after 
guard bombs started fires gates says adding that he has briefly 
evacuated his business three times because of the fires 
theyll be shooting airtoground incendiary rockets and 
everybody else cant burn trash he says 
alstotts group has filed a lawsuit challenging the scope of 
training at the camp and seeking to enforce the original agreement 
in 1913 under which only the michigan militia could train at the 
camp 
one problem is lowflight corridors established years ago 
before multiengined jets which are a lot nosier we get 
complaints about wrecking peace and quiet says lt col brian 
downey spokesman for the michigan guard 
occasionally residents near the ranges report cracked windows 
and fallen plaster after an exercise if an investigation 
establishes the damage was caused by the training the guard pays 
for the repairs 
one of the bombing ranges is near guthrie lake on the northwest 
border of the camp this spring otsego lake township assessor 
lorrie chapman cut the value of houses off the lake itself by 50 
percent 
more than likely she said its because of the bombing at 
the bombing range 
to keep the noise down and to streamline training downey said a 
new computerized mock war zone will be built farther inside the 
camps boundaries 
downey said as part of the armys total force concept the 
multipurpose range complex combines tank infantry and helicopter 
training with computerized targets the range will be nestled 
between two rises in the land which should cut noise he added 
gates group strongly opposes the complex saying it lies in the 
au sable watershed area and in addition to noise may result in 
pollution of the river because of the explosives 
in grayling itself many in the business community welcome the 
guard at this summers peak about 8000 troops will train at the 
camp 
its an advantage says mary holden manager of a small 
downtown hotel theyve kept us in business for years 
