editors note the idea was to build a new capital city to open 
up and populate brazils empty central region that it did the 
gleaming futuristic city also lured throngs of miserably poor 
peasants hoping to find jobs nobody counted on the resulting 
overcrowding in a perimeter of satellite cities brasilia as one 
official puts it is now a fantasy island surrounded by misery 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
it was called the capital of hope and 
the capital of the future when it was built 28 years ago a 
modernistic city rising from scratch in the middle of a dry and 
barren prairie 750 miles from the sea 
today brazils capital has become both a capital of despair and 
a paradise of plenty a city of wretched poverty and gleaming 
opulence 
some say brasilia is the victim of its own success 
brasilia was a modern option and was useful because it did 
what it set out to do decentralize the country build new highways 
and transfer the seat of government says oscar niemeyer the 
architect of the slickwhite linear buildings that are brasilias 
landmarks 
but brasilia also symbolizes the spirit of brazil which is 
discriminatory and lacks social justice adds niemeyer now 81 
only a revolution will solve our problems 
built to sustain 2 million people by the year 2000 brasilias 
federal district already has a population of 17 million by the 
end of the century that number is expected to swell to 4 million 
a population the city cannot support under present conditions 
when it was planned the growth of the city was not imagined 
by anyone says federal district gov jose de oliveira aparecido 
it is now like a beautiful woman wearing old clothes it needs to 
be modernized 
today brasilia has the social ills of other large brazilian 
cities overcrowding shantytowns land invasions homeless 
children and traffic jams 
a lack of water magnified by a dry season which sponges 
soothing humidity from the air adds to brasilias woes 
although brasilia was planned to house the powerful who run the 
political and administrative machinery the poor are now the 
majority 
lured by the very promise of the citys founders the poor come 
in tattered clothes and plastic thongs to escape the drought and 
famine of the northeast 
they come to find their dreams but when they get here they 
realize its not the promised land aparecido says 
unable to survive in a city where only the affluent can afford 
to live they end up in one of brasilias 11 satellite cities 
located 15 to 80 miles away 
federal congresswoman maria de lourdes abadia has called 
brasilia a fantasy island surrounded by misery 
ceilandia one of the poorest satellite cities didnt exist in 
1970 and today has nearly half a million people 
a promised landreform program to distribute fertile land to 12 
million landless peasants is stalled attracting even more to the 
capital of hope 
brazil a developing nation larger than the continental united 
states has 143 million people and the worlds eighthlargest 
economy but 70 percent of its people live in dire poverty and earn 
less than 45 a week in a country which last year had inflation of 
366 percent 
unoccupied cultivable land is scarce and most of it belongs to 
just 4 percent of the population as it has for centuries 
without land without money or technology to improve their 
lives the rural workers will continue to invade the city 
niemeyer says 
brasilia was erected in a flash of resolve it was the campaign 
platform of president juscelino kubitschek who took office in 
1956 to create a capital that would unite the whole nation 
four years later on april 21 1960 as kubitschek promised 
brasilia was inaugurated 
at the time the capital was rio de janeiro a tropical city of 
spectacular mountains and beaches and a vibrant nightlife 
few wanted to move to an artificial barren city full of red 
dirt and brush land brasilia far inland in the state of goias 
didnt even have one river or spring 
but there was no choice many foreign embassies were threatened 
with losing accreditation if they didnt move to the new capital 
there was no way of avoiding it the lungs of brazil are in 
brasilia it is center of national power says aparecido often 
criticized because he spends much time visiting other capitals 
such as paris and rome 
last year largely through aparecidos efforts brasilia became 
the youngest city to be named by the united nations as a patrimony 
of mankind a cultural and historical heritage 
shaped like an airplane brasilias nucleus is called the 
pilot plan the design of architect and urbanist lucio costa 
now 86 
in brasilias cockpit is the government the futuristic 
marbled buildings which carry the unmistakable swirling seal of 
architect niemeyer 
visitors are drawn to the marbled and spacious presidential 
palace where president jose sarney on most fridays makes a grand 
exit walking down a swooping ramp to his limousine 
the twintowered whitedomed congress where lawmakers are 
writing a new constitution inside chambers connected by underground 
tunnels becomes on weekends a playground for children who climb 
the domes like ants on a hill 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880516-0252 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
like rows of disciplined soldiers identical government 
ministries line a wide esplanade that leads into the residential 
and commercial sectors 
in the wings of the brasilian plane are businesses and 
apartments called the superquadras or superblocks identified 
only by letters and numbers most superquadras have their own large 
supermarket and smaller bread shops a brazilian version of 
stopandgo shopping 
landscape artist roberto burle marx relieved brasilias cool 
uniformity with a mosaic of gardens and trees the idea was to 
accentuate the wide horizons and open sky of a city that had no 
hills forest or sea 
brasilia was not planned for pedestrians by car it is easy and 
fast to drive down its avenues and looping highways 
but it is difficult and slow to get around if you are one of the 
million who pour in daily from the satellite cities to work there 
arent enough buses fares are expensive and the ride can be 
dangerous bad drivers as well as poorly maintained buses account 
for 200 accidents a month 
maria dos santos a maid who works in brasilia earns 70 
dollars a month she she spends half that to take three buses into 
the city 
besides the satellite cities some 10 favelas portuguese 
for ghettos or shantytowns have recently sprung up including one 
a couple of miles from the alvorada palace where sarney resides 
an empty lot usually government property is an invitation for 
squatters to build cardboard houses recently 900 descended on a 
plot next to a trendy apartment building 
with no water or electricity the settlement was a health hazard 
as well as an eyesore eventually police on horseback torched the 
shacks and dispersed the squatters 
to keep migrants away the government has begun paying families 
to return to their home states in its initial stage few are 
taking up the offer 
the cost of living in brasilia is about the same as in rio or 
sao paulo but the quality of life can be better for the welltodo 
in brasilia 
for example in the residential area surrounding an artificial 
lake a threebedroom house with a pool rents for about 1000 a 
month in rio it would be double that 
apartments in brasilia rent for about 200 to 600 a month 
depending on the desirability of the block 
aparecido boasts brasilia has the best quality of life of any 
city in brazil where else can you have such space for so little 
that applies only to the elite 
in ceilandia a simple onebedroom house with just a kitchen and 
bath rents for about 50 a month about as much as the occupant 
could hope to earn 
brasilia has expensive restaurants and cheap restaurants 
nothing in between with prices at the fine restaurants varying 
from 20 to 40 for two people 
middlelevel professionals such as university professors and 
bankers earn 800 to 1000 a month a lot by brazilian standards a 
member of congress however gets 7000 a month tax exempt 
for fun the poor stay in their satellite cities if they come 
in they can hang out in one of the many corner bars which sell the 
popular and cheap sugar cane liquor called cachaca or go to a 
movie a meal at a simple restaurant can be less than 5 a person 
the affluent go to one of the dozen tennis golf or sailing 
clubs along the lake which charge a membership of 60 to 100 a 
month 
since every other lakeside house has a swimming pool 
entertaining at home is popular theres not much else to do with 
few museums theaters and concerts available for either the poor or 
rich 
niemeyer and costa have plans for new residential areas to take 
the weight off the districts overloaded plane 
some officials say brasilias most crucial problem is lack of 
water 
the main dam built in the 1960s to supply water for 350000 
people is serving at least twice that many the artificial lake 
used as a humidifier and for sewage drainage is polluted and 
infested with hardy weeds 
for nearly six months a year brasilias humidity levels dip to 
below 20 percent last year levels dropped to 7 percent the 
average at the sahara desert is 13 percent what the world health 
organizaton says is the limit for humans 
water rationing is now standard during the dry season but city 
water officials foresee harder times 
we need funds to buy technology to clean up the lake and build 
another dam and another lake says valdo roholf vice president of 
brasilias water company we say it will be cheaper than building 
a new capital 
