<DOCNO> AP880516-0257 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
about 10000 people marched in the central city of brasov this 
past november to demand higher wages more food and for ceausescu 
to resign but the diplomats say the formation of a mass movement 
like the solidarity trade union in poland is unlikely in romania 
romanians express their dissatisfaction only in whispers 
one whispered story intended as a joke is about a romanian who 
regularly asks at communist party meetings where has all the 
meat gone he soon disappears when his companion asks what 
happened to his friend he is greeted with stony silence 
since the brasov protest diplomats have noted tightened 
security and more uniformed militia in towns and cities 
foreigners movements are increasingly restricted some western 
journalists have been picked up by police or expelled 
romanians are obliged to report any contacts with foreigners 
many refuse even to answer a foreigners request for directions 
even the few officials allowed to give interviews to foreigners 
do so only on condition they are not identified by name 
ceausescu has come under increasing pressure from the west and 
even the east bloc over human rights 
neighboring hungary an ally in the east blocs warsaw pact has 
voiced unprecedented criticism of what it sees as discrimination 
against romanias ethnic hungarian minority a highly sensitive 
issue for romanian authorities 
an ap reporter traveling recently through transylvania in the 
north where most of the 2 million ethnic hungarians and 220000 
ethnic germans live was picked up by police and told to return 
immediately to bucharest the capital 
despite attempts to attract western currency through tourism 
foreigners and foreign cars are rare in romania 
children wave and smile when a foreign car passes drivers of 
the romanianmade dacia car which dominates the roads often flash 
their lights in greeting 
a more common sight in the countryside are horsedrawn carts 
carrying livestock or hay and exhausted slumbering farm workers 
the countryside reveals lush green wheat fields rich red earth 
freshly tilled for planting fat pigs and large herds of sheep but 
the eye is often jarred by sprawling chemical plants puffing black 
smoke out over the pastures 
vegetable supplies at private markets are sparse mainly root 
vegetables or great mounds of paprika spice there is no fruit 
while city dwellers line up for hours for food and other 
essentials peasants and villagers must often trudge miles to get 
their produce to market 
officials say a plan to establish agroindustrial centers and to 
modernize cities is aimed at improving living standards 
an official from the national council of city halls said the 
project is designed to put industry at the source of raw materials 
and provide hospitals schools and social services for more people 
in the new centers he said one family member could work in 
industry while the rest tilled the land thus preventing the 
traditional drift from rural to urban communities 
the average monthly wage in romania is 3035 lei 347 at the 
official rate of exchange but farmers income is lower 
the agroindustrial centers could mean that as many 6000 
villages eventually will vanish 
its going to the heart of romanian society a diplomat 
said noting the project makes it easier to control people and will 
strip peasants of what independence they now have 
in cities modernization has led to widespread demolition 
in bucharest for example 28 churches and synagogues have been 
destroyed to make way for a palatial center to house communist 
party headquarters the building looks out over an avenue more than 
a half mile long lined with sculpted white apartment blocks and 
derisively called the champs elysees of the balkans by 
romanians 
work on the project is done night and day as the city falls 
into darkness with only dim street lighting the floodlit 
construction dominates the skyline 
</TEXT>
