<TEXT>
this picturesque city is the cultural heart 
of romanias hungarian minority who have become a cause of 
friction between two soviet bloc allies 
for centuries hungarians romanians and germans fought over and 
settled the historic region of transylvania they developed a rich 
culture and a tradition so intertwined that no part of transylvania 
seems exclusively characteristic of one nationality 
but since the mid1980s this cultural blend has been upset by 
an escalating war of words between romania and hungary which have 
long contested each others claims to transylvania 
the hungarian government charges that romania is discriminating 
against 2 million ethnic hungarians by deemphasizing the hungarian 
language in education diluting hungarian culture by moving more 
romanians into traditional hungarian areas and sending hungarians 
to work in romanian areas 
similar actions are being taken against transylvanias 220000 
ethnic germans but the germans have been emigrtating to west 
germany at a rapid rate 
since april official publications in the hungarian and german 
languages have been allowed to use only romanian versions of place 
names reports also are circulating that romanian authorities no 
longer are registering typical hungarian names for hungarian babies 
and that this could also lead to the banning of hungarian family 
names 
many street signs in cluj are still in both hungarian and 
romanian but in tirgu mures a town that is 50 percent hungarian 
40 miles to the east the signs are only in romanian 
hungarian is spoken openly in the region however in cluj 
where about 35 to 40 percent of the population is hungarian roman 
catholic mass is celebrated daily in hungarian 
but the hungarians are not allowed to subscribe to publications 
from hungary 
five years ago clujs university offered instruction in 
hungarian and romanian but today hungarian is used only in one 
course hungarian philology which has just five students 
the german minority has been decreasing steadily for years 
dropping from 800000 in 1939 to some 220000 today 
ethnic german emigration to west germany is so rapid that one 
small church has seen its parishioners decline from 2000 to just 
over 300 in seven years 
</TEXT>
