<TEXT>
in a babys first months of life the most common 
cause of crying is something called colic 
its cause is unclear but not its effects infants cry 
inconsolably often for hours on end 
sometimes their bellies are bulging and gassy but experts 
believe this is a result rather than a cause because colicky 
babies gulp air as they wail 
colic eventually goes away but in the meantime sleep expert 
dr richard ferber of childrens hospital says there are a few 
things parents can do 
sometimes walking the baby or rubbing his back will help if 
this fails simply leaving the child alone for a while may calm him 
down 
colicky infants may cry because they are overly sensitive to 
things happening around them or they are handled and stimulated too 
much 
if the baby is not easily comforted leave him alone in his crib 
for 15 to 30 minutes feeding or gentle softspoken consoling may 
then quiet him if it doesnt let him cry another 15 to 30 minutes 
ferber believes letting babies cry alone this way lets them 
release their builtup tensions 
</TEXT>
