<TEXT>
in a federal laboratory just up the road from 
the university of georgia sit dozens of pyrex beakers filled with 
moldy spoon size shredded wheat 
the mess in the beakers is the work of a selfdescribed 
simpleminded briton who finds in his fungi the stuff of an 
agricultural revolution natural compounds that can do the work of 
harmful chemicals 
hank cutler is a plant physiologist at the us department of 
agricultures richard b russell research center a highrise that 
borders the university campus but which few students ever visit 
to describe his work cutler likes to explain how discovery of 
penicillin from the penicillium mold turned medicine away from the 
use of dangerous metals for drugs and toward the use of natural 
antibiotics the same sort of thing is happening in agriculture 
perhaps now we need agricultural chemicals that are biodegradable 
and dont impact the environment 
cutler grows fungi often using as his medium spoon size 
shredded wheat with its little crosshatch pieces the cereal 
seems to work just fine for growing mold just add a little yeast 
and sugar 
he later filters the mold to fine compounds that might have some 
biological action of their own 
there may be 30 40 50 compounds in there and ive got to 
get out the one thats active thats the art i see something 
interesting in that gunk and i say how the hell am i going to 
get it out of there 
some of the compounds hes found include 
cyclopenin a chemical from penicillium mold that acts as a 
tranquilizer on baby chicks it contains the same structural 
elements as diazepam the drug sold as valium cutler said it 
also retards growth in some plants 
cyclopenol which kills the fungus that caused the great irish 
potato famine and still attacks crops 
cytochalasinh which controls flowering in certain plants 
cutlers latest discovery is a compound he grew from special 
wine grapes and dubbed cinereain 
its not terribly active but i bet that it will have 
significant pharmaceutical activity because structurally it 
resembles other compounds used in the pharmaceutical industry he 
said thats a hunch im probably dead wrong but i can 
guarantee you its got biological activity 
cutlers findings on cinereain will be published next month by 
the japanese journal agricultural and biological chemistry i 
like to publish on their turf because i then know that im highly 
competitive he said 
cutler whos made a career of studying fungi the last 20 years 
in georgia for the usda fears the united states is falling behind 
the far east in agricultural biochemistry american agriculture has 
been liberal with nonbiodegradable farm chemicals japan with its 
land constraints has turned to chemicals that dont harm the 
environment 
i believe very strongly that within the next five to seven 
years we will be importing japanese agricultural chemicals based on 
natural products he said and well be wringing our hands 
just like the automobile and saying gee whiz what happened 
