<TEXT>
researchers say theyre encouraged by a new 
method of fighting one of the main obstacles facing leukemia 
victims who need bone marrow transplants a disease in which the 
transplanted marrow attacks the body 
graftversushost disease is the reverse of the reaction wherein 
the body rejects a transplanted organ dr roy wu of the national 
cancer institute says more recipients die from gvhd than from 
relapses of their leukemia 
in the new method johns hopkins oncology center researchers 
used a centrifuge to remove tlymphocytes immune system components 
that trigger rejection then implanted cellrich marrow necessary 
for the production of healthy blood and for successful grafts they 
also administered cyclosporin an antirejection drug that doctors 
had been using as part of leukemia treatment 
the 12month survival rate for patients treated with cyclosporin 
is only about 35 percent dr albert donnenberg of johns hopkins 
says 50 percent of patients receiving the new treatment survived 
the year patients who began the new treatment while in remission 
for leukemia had a 63 percent survival rate compared with 39 
percent for patients who were in early relapse 
donnenberg says it is too early to claim success because the 
center has not done a controlled study in which two groups are 
treated and studied 
