<TEXT>
as computer data bases cassettes and compact 
discs join newspapers magazines and books the united states is 
confronting a shortage of public librarians to help sort the flood 
of information a large number of librarians will be retiring in 
the next five to 10 years and there arent the numbers coming in to 
replace them said margaret myers a personnel expert with the 
american library association 
 
she said library schools had 3538 graduates in 1986 fewer than 
half the 8091 degrees in 1979 
 
the shortfall comes as the public needs librarians trained to 
help make sense of the new books data bases videocassettes 
specialist magazines and countless other media that debut daily 
ms myers said recently 
childrens librarians school media specialists catalogers and 
minority service personnel are in particularly short supply 
experts say some openings go unfilled others are staffed by less 
qualified workers 
in some geographic areas its a crisis new york boston the 
east coast said ala president margaret chisholm theres such 
a shortage that it is really affecting services 
 
among the causes cited for the shortage are new corporate 
opportunities an overall increase in the number of public library 
jobs and low pay for librarians 
 
average starting salaries for new york city librarians with 
masters degrees in library science are 22500 said library 
spokeswoman lauren moye a national survey of 1986 library school 
masters graduates indicated starting salaries averaged 20874 
school librarians averaged 28390 last year reference workers 
in public and academic libraries were paid an average 23552 in 
1986 and staff in special libraries including corporations 
averaged 28943 in 1985 according to studies 
 
librarians in the west and southwest tend to make higher 
salaries said ms myers lowest salaries are in the 
southeast 
once one of the few professions open to women public and school 
library careers are now just one of many options 
 
libraries and nursing cannot compete with law and banking 
said ed szynaka library director in suburban pasadena you could 
start with a five figure salary in law that could be as high as 
you would ever get in a library career 
 
those who stick with library training are finding better pay 
working in corporate libraries and data bases rather than public 
libraries the corporate openings listed at ala meetings outstrip 
the number of interviewees said myers 
 
a california library association report predicts 1988 will bring 
364 public academic and specialized librarian openings 256 of 
them in public libraries next year 446 openings are expected 
statewide 
while the survey projected 60 percent of the openings will be in 
public libraries only 28 percent of the 162 library school 
students responding to the survey want public library work 
thirtyfive percent prefer academic libraries and 26 percent 
special libraries 
salaries are better in the private sector than in the public 
sector said mary sue farrell executive director of the state 
library association salaries are better at gte or ibm than 
working for the city of san francisco 
 
along with the need for childrens librarians the survey also 
pinpointed an underrepresentation of minorities in the profession 
as compared with the population of california especially among 
hispanics and blacks 
with shortages of both childrens and school librarians experts 
are worried that young people may not gain the skills needed to 
sort information gained from reading books or magazines typing 
queries on a computer terminal using a microfiche reader or 
viewing from a compact disc if you have a school of 3000 kids 
and you dont have a librarian there thats a problem said 
bonnie obrian the los angeles school library 
supervisor almost every job people are going into has to do 
with information the only place they can learn that is in the 
school library media center 
