<TEXT>
jobseekers with a disability probably shouldnt mention it on 
their resume waiting instead until they are invited for an 
interview says a university of michigan administrator 
once hired disabled people have proven themselves to be 
important members of the work force in terms of both numbers and 
achievement notes darlys vander beek director of disabled student 
services at the ann arbor mich institution 
vander beek says about 14 percent of the labor force has some 
kind of disability 20 percent if substance abusers are included 
one of the most frequent questions asked by disabled persons is 
whether to list a disability on a resume she says adding that 
some say it is only fair to employers while others believe it may 
eliminate the applicant from consideration 
i would say to not put it on a resume unless you are applying 
to a place where your disability would be a definite asset or 
where youll be working with a lot of disabled people vander 
beek suggests 
otherwise dont bring it up until you have been invited for 
an interview 
vander beek says that legally potential employers cannot ask 
about a disability unless they can prove job performance would be 
affected studies show however that those who openly discuss the 
matter with interviewers tend to be more successful in their 
jobseeking she adds 
but if a disability is not visible and wont affect the job 
dont bring it up because old stereotypes still linger she says 
