<TEXT>
nothing makes a worse impression on prospective employers than 
an applicant who arrives late for a job interview and the key to 
success in the facetoface meeting is projecting a natural and 
confident manner 
so says a job placement executive for an indianapolisbased 
technical school network 
our employers judge job candidates on first impressions 
taking particular note of enthusiasm interest and appearance 
according to connie welborn national placement director for itt 
educational services inc 
in addition to tardiness she advises there are several other 
common interview blunders that should be avoided including 
dressing inappropriately asking too many questions criticizing 
former employers and not doing your homework 
since employers get their first impression from the applicants 
appearance the safest choice of what to wear is a conservative 
suit or dress in navy gray or tan with equally businesslike 
accessories 
as for asking questions welborn suggests a few will demonstrate 
your enthusiasm but they should be limited to three or four about 
the company and the job opening 
criticism and gossip about former employers will brand the 
applicant as a complainer she advises while on the other hand the 
job interviewer might be impressed by applicants who have bothered 
to familiarize themselves with the companys most recent 
developments 
other common mistakes include 
discussing personal and financial problems the interviewer 
wants to hear about your training and experience not your 
financial woes keep your personal life to yourself 
not knowing your strengths be prepared to speak about 
yourself and why you are suited to the job opening 
lack of training and education you shouldnt waste 
someones time if you know that your education does not meet the 
minimum requirements remember if you lack the skills its never 
too late to enroll in a training program 
not following up if you are not offered the job on the 
spot be sure to send a brief note to thank the interviewer for his 
time it is also a great way to express your interest 
irvin marek director of the career planning and placement 
office at chicagos loyola university has similar suggestions for 
jobseekers adding 
dont slouch fidget chew gum or smoke be positive be 
courteous be yourself 
successful research successful practice successful questions 
lead to success look forward to the job interview as an 
opportunity to sell yourself to the organization you want to join 
one of the more important elements in a job interview may be 
your voice says a professional voice consultant 
the trick is to be able to convey a strong sense of 
confidence even if you feel like jelly inside says william 
rush who is also an adviser to the halls voice improvement program 
some of his tips for job interviewing 
recognize that you will be nervous consciously slow down your 
inner tempo take a few deep breaths to make it easier for you to 
speak 
remember to enunciate consonant sounds and avoid mumbling 
watch your posture keep your shoulders back and spine 
straight 
pause briefly after each important thought or word to add 
emphasis 
try to anticipate the questions your interviewer might ask 
you will convey your messages more confidently when those topics do 
come up 
</TEXT>
