<TEXT>
economic growth in the industrialized democracies 
will be much quicker in both 1988 and 1989 than was thought at the 
end of last year following the october markets crash according to 
oecd projections released monday 
the organization for economic cooperation and development 
confirmed that it has revised upward its projection for real or 
inflationadjusted gross national product growth to 3 percent for 
1988 from its december estimate of 225 percent 
the growth rate for 1989 is now expected to be around 25 
percent compared with a previous estimate of 175 percent 
the oecd which is made up of the worlds 24 most industrialized 
nations is now projecting that real growth in the united states 
will reach 275 percent in 1988 slowing slightly to 25 percent in 
1989 these figures were revised upward from the december estimates 
of 25 and 175 percent respectively 
growth rates in other major oecd member countries have also been 
adjusted west germany is expected to experience a 225 percent 
expansion in 1988 slowing to 175 percent in 1989 compared with 
earlier estimates of 15 percent and 175 percent respectively 
japan will have one of the strongest growth rates among the 
major industrialized countries with a projected 425 percent this 
year and 375 percent in 1989 the oecd said this compares with 
december forecasts of 35 percent and 3 percent respectively 
the latest oecd figures for inflation are littlechanged from 
those of the december 1987 outlook with rates of 35 percent 
expected for the 24 oecd member countries in 1988 and 375 percent 
projected for 1989 
on unemployment the oecd sees the average rate for the 
industrialized countries as a group at 75 percent in both 1988 and 
1989 compared with previous estimates of 8 percent for 1988 and 
825 percent for 1989 
