the supreme court today refused to exempt 
federally chartered international banks from being taxed by states 
and cities where the banks have branch offices 
the court citing the lack of a substantial federal 
question let stand a ruling that continental bank international 
a subsidiary of chicagobased continental illinois national bank amp 
trust co must pay more than 6 million in taxes penalties and 
interest to new york city 
justice byron r white voted to hear the banks appeal but four 
votes are needed to grant such review 
the new york court of appeals the states highest court ruled 
last february continental is not exempt from the citys financial 
corporation tax 
city officials said the banks new york city branch owed 6075 
million for the periods sept 1 1980 to dec 31 1980 and jan 1 
1981 to dec 31 1981 
congress authorized federally chartered international banks in a 
1919 law the edge act to supply international credit and to 
secure foreign trade markets for us exports 
the federal reserve board regulates the banks which were given 
expanded power by congress in 1978 to mobilize resources to 
increase american overseas trade 
there are some 90 such banks with most of their offices 
concentrated in california florida illinois new york and texas 
continental international argued that like a federally 
chartered national bank it should be exempt from state and local 
taxes unless congress specifically authorized otherwise 
but the new york court said international banks are not 
federal instrumentalities entitled to constitutional immunity from 
tax 
the state court also said there is nothing in federal law to 
suggest congress intended to exempt branch offices of such banks 
from state and city taxes 
an intention of congress to deny the states power to tax edge 
act bank branches cannot be inferred from the language of the 
statute which is at best ambiguous on that subject the state 
court said 
the reagan administration endorsed the state court ruling 
justice department lawyers responding to a supreme court 
invitation to comment said the 1919 laws fairest reading is 
that it should not be interpreted to preclude taxation by 
states in which branch offices are located 
the case is continental bank vs new york city 861857 
