<TEXT>
the supreme court upheld on monday a 18 
million judgment against an insurance company that had been ordered 
to pay the money to an injured mississippi man whose 20000 claim 
it wrongfully rejected 
but the justices declined to decide the constitutionality of 
large punitive damage awards in personal injury cases 
in another case the court ruled the federal communications 
commission has exclusive authority to regulate the technical 
quality of cable television signals it rejected arguments that 
state and local officials should be allowed to impose more 
stringent requirements for cable tv 
the court also agreed to decide whether new jersey unfairly is 
forcing 13 major oil companies to pay millions of dollars in taxes 
by denying state tax deductions for what the companies pay in 
federal windfall profits taxes 
in other major businessrelated rulings the court 
refused to exempt federally chartered international banks from 
being taxed by states and cities where the banks have branch 
offices the court let stand a ruling that continental bank 
international based in chicago must pay more than 6 million in 
taxes penalties and interest to new york city 
made it easier for people to file jobdiscrimination charges 
against employers by allowing flexibility for meeting some 
deadlines imposed by a federal antibias law the justices agreed 
with the reagan administration and revived a colorado sex 
discrimination case that was dismissed because deadlines for filing 
the complaint were missed 
let stand a decision generally barring foreign car 
manufacturers from forcing franchised us dealers to buy 
replacement parts exclusively from them it rejected an appeal by 
mercedesbenz of north america inc that had been supported by 
other foreign and domestic car makers 
ruled that states may tax the costs of producing merchandise 
catalogs mailed directly to instate residents even when the 
catalogs are published in other states the court unanimously 
rejected an attempt by a new orleansbased department store chain 
to avoid paying taxes for catalogs received by its louisiana 
customers 
in the insurance case the court left unresolved the question of 
skyrocketing damage awards some states reacting to soaring 
insurance rates have imposed ceilings on how much money can be 
recovered in personal injury lawsuits 
justice thurgood marshall writing for the the court said 
settling the issue now would shortcircuit a number of less 
intrusive and possibly more appropriate resolutions 
the justices did decide a lesser issue raised in the dispute 
upholding a mississippi law that imposed a 15 percent penalty 
243000 against the insurance company for unsuccesfully 
appealing the case to the mississippi supreme court the vote on 
that issue was 61 
the case involved lloyd crenshaw of pascagoula miss whose leg 
was amputated less than two weeks after he injured it in his garage 
in 1979 
crenshaw 61 at the time worked at the white stores in 
pascagoula his employer had a group insurance policy with bankers 
life and casualty co 
a state jury ruled that bankers life acted in bad faith in 
denying crenshaws claim and awarded him 20000 in actual damages 
and 16 million in punitive damages 
the insurance company said the punitive damage judgment violates 
the constitution but that issue was not raised or passed upon by 
the mississippi courts 
in the cable television case the court said the fcc acted 
within the statutory authority conferred by congress when it 
preempted state and local technical standards governing the 
quality of cable television signals 
the fcc has divided cable services into four categories the 
first consists of cable channels that deliver signals of television 
stations that are normally broadcast through the air 
the other classes include cable channels such as cable news 
network and espn pay channels such as home box office and 
channels with twoway interaction capability 
the us circuit court of appeals ruled last year the fcc has 
exclusive control over the signal quality of the first class of 
cable channels the appeals court also ordered the fcc to develop 
standards for assuring the quality of the signals in the latter 
three categories 
the first part of the appeals court ruling was appealed by the 
national league of cities new york city officials and other 
communities who said state county and city governments should be 
allowed to impose signal quality standards for cable channels that 
carry television broadcast stations 
in its ruling the supreme court said a 1984 federal law 
endorses a dual system of cable tv regulation giving local 
officials power to award franchises but leaving control over 
technical quality of cable signals with the fcc 
in the new jersey tax case the oil companies which operate 
numerous refineries in the state challenged a state business tax 
law that disallows a deduction for windfall profits tax payments 
the companies said the state tax is unfair because the windfall 
profits tax is based on oil production none of which takes place 
in new jersey 
the new jersey supreme court upheld the state tax last june 
saying it does not discriminate unfairly against the oil companies 
the oil companies paid an extra 885 million in taxes to new 
jersey from 1980 through 1984 because of the state tax disallowance 
the tax challenge was mounted by amerada hess atlantic 
richfield conoco cities service exxon phillips petroleum 
chevron mobil oil union oil of california gulf oil shell oil 
tenneco oil and texaco 
